We recommended that Management adopt the recommended procedural flowchart in the procurement and distribution of food supplies (Annex 6) pursuant to the afore-cited law and regulations, taking into consideration the lack of personnel in the LGU.  The following are the recommended changes in the procedures:

The Local Chief Executive expedite the recruitment and hiring of a full-time and qualified General Services Officer (GSO);

The inspection of deliveries of food supplies purchased shall be conducted by the personnel presently assigned as inspector and shall be accepted in the Acceptance and Inspection Report (AIR), prepared in two copies, by the MSWDO, in the meantime that there is no full-time GSO. The MSWDO shall then keep the second copy of the report for recording in the stock cards while the first copy shall be forwarded to the Municipal Accountant, together with the Delivery Receipt/Sales Invoice, for recording in the books of accounts and subsidiary records; 

The custody of the food supplies shall be the responsibility of the MSWDO until issuance thereof to the requesting party/barangay. A Requisition Issue Slip (RIS) shall be prepared by the MSWDO for signature by the concerned Punong Barangay based on the Relief Distribution Sheet (RDS) prepared by her office. Further, the MSWDO, in the meantime that there is no full-time GSO, shall also be responsible in maintaining and recording in the stock cards the details of the inventories received, distributed and its balance;

The Municipal Accountant shall adopt the perpetual inventory method in recording the food supplies procured. The AIR and other supporting documents shall be the basis in the preparation of the DV and recording of deliveries in the books and the appropriate ledger cards;  

The MSWDO shall be responsible for the proper distribution of the food supplies to the barangays/recipients;

A Requisition Issue Slip (RIS) (numbered based on RIS logbook) shall be prepared by the MSWDO, in four (4) copies, upon request of welfare goods by the concerned punong barangay as basis for the issuance thereof, copies of which are distributed as follows:

Copy 1- Accounting, to be submitted together with the SSMI at the end of the month by the MSWDO

Copy 2- Requesting Party/Punong Barangay 

Copy 3- MSWDO, to be attached to the RDLs upon receipt thereof  from the concerned punong barangay

Copy 4- File copy of MSWDO

The RIS Logbook, which shall be maintained by the MSWDO, shall have the following column headings: RIS No., Date, Description and Quantity of Food Supplies to be Issued, Name of Requesting Party, Position/Designation, Official Station or Address and Signature.

After properly accomplishing and approval of the RIS, the MSWDO shall withdraw from stock and shall issue the food supplies to the punong barangay or other officials/persons authorized to receive the goods;

On a weekly or monthly basis, the MSWDO shall promptly prepare the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI), based on the RIS for the distributed supplies, which shall be submitted to the Municipal Accountant, together with the Accountant’s copy of the RIS, for recording;

The Municipal Accountant shall prepare the JEV to record the food supplies expense based on the SSMIs and RISs received from the MSWDO;

The MSWDO shall require all requesting parties to submit the properly accomplished RDL within 15 days after the distribution of the food supplies to the beneficiaries.  She shall conduct regular monitoring of the submission thereof and follow up with the concerned requesting parties who failed to submit the pertinent RDL;

The MSWDO shall prepare and submit the liquidation report per RIS, once the RDLs are complete, to the Municipal Accountant for review and submission to the Auditor, instead of directly attaching the documents to the disbursement vouchers;  

The Municipal Accountant and MSWDO shall regularly reconcile their respective records to determine any errors in recording of food supplies procurement, issuances and balances;

The PPMPs shall be submitted by each Department/Office of the Municipal Government to the Municipal Budget Office and shall be evaluated and included in the proposed Annual Budget for approval. After approval of the proposed Annual Budget, the Municipal Budget Officer shall furnish a copy of the same, together with the corresponding PPMPs, to the BAC Secretariat for its review and consolidation into the proposed APP; 

The BAC shall evaluate the APP and determine the applicable mode of procurement for each goods or services to be procured contained therein.  After evaluation, the BAC shall issue a Resolution recommending the modes of procurement for all the items to be procured and forwards the same, together with the APP, to the Mayor for approval;  

A copy of the BAC Resolution, together with the approved APP, shall be furnished each Department as basis for the preparation of Purchase Request on goods or services needed for the quarter at the beginning of the year and of each subsequent quarter.

We reiterated prior year’s recommendations that Management:
reconstitute the Inventory Committee that will take charge in the conduct of a thorough and complete physical inventory of the Municipality’s properties, thereafter, prepare the RPCPPE in the prescribed form as shown in Annex 49 of the NGAS Manual for LGUs, Volume II, and submit the same to the Auditor not later than January 31 of each year;
direct the Inventory Committee to determine and indicate in the RPCPPE the actual quantity on hand and the physical condition of the properties for proper measurement of its carrying amount in the financial statements;
direct the Property Officer to assign the corresponding Property Name and Number for all PPE items for proper identification.
Additionally, we recommended that Management implement the “One-Time Cleansing of PPE accounts” as provided under COA Circular No. 2020-006 to establish PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive require:

The Inventory Committee to conduct an inventory of the local roads under the LGU’s jurisdiction and prepare the Report on the Physical Count of Road Network System;

The designated General Service Officer to render a report on Local Road Network at the end of the accounting period, maintain a Local Road Inventory and Road Map and keep a complete Local Road Network Property Cards for all roads and its components;

The Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects;

The Municipal Accountant to keep and maintain subsidiary records for roads and road components for every road network and reconcile the same to the result of the physical inventory taking at the end of each year; and

The Municipal Accountant to include the necessary disclosure on the total road network system in the Notes to the Financial Statements.

We recommended that Management:

Adopt prescribed control procedures in the receipt, inventory and issuance of donations- in kind, and record the proper cost of the ending inventory based on the value declared by the donor, if available, or using the prevailing market price of the donated items in the books or in the registries, as applicable;

Require the concerned offices/units to properly categorize the Donations- in Kind received by the Municipality and intended for COVID-19 response and other calamities reported in the Summary/List of Donations Received, Distributed and Balances for consolidation;

Require the MDRRMO to submit a consolidated report on Summary/List of Donations Received, Distributed and Balances, separately for Cash and In-Kind transactions for CY 2020 and onwards, to the NDRRMC through the OCD, copy furnished the Auditor, as required in COA Circular 2014-002 and 2020-009;

Require the assigned staff in Office of the Mayor to maintain Registry of Donated Relief Goods for DRRM to properly account for the ending inventory balances; 

Require the Municipal Accountant to disclose in the Notes to Financial Statements information pertaining to DRRM not evident on the face of the financial statements;

We recommended that Management direct its concerned Officers to:

Fully implement GAD activities and programs; 

Avoid over estimations in the preparation of the GAD Plan and Budget;

Make the necessary adjustments to the GAD Plan and Budget as the need arises; and

Regularly monitor the implementation of GAD activities and programs in order to fully maximize the potential benefits that the intended beneficiaries can derive therefrom.

